{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","language":"python","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"accelerator":"GPU","kaggle":{"accelerator":"nvidiaTeslaT4","dataSources":[],"dockerImageVersionId":31329,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":true}},"nbformat_minor":5,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"id":"8beacf83-052f-4747-81bb-19239bdfc9b4","cell_type":"markdown","source":"# AI-SOCO — Atribución de Autoría de Código Fuente\n- Angel Mauricio Ramírez Herrera | A01710158\n- Emiliano Gomez Gonzalez | A01710711\n\nEl objetivo es identificar al autor de un fragmento de código fuente a partir de su estilo de programación. \nEl dataset AI-SOCO contiene soluciones a problemas de programación competitiva escritas por 1,000 autores distintos. \nSe comparan tres enfoques ordenados de menor a mayor complejidad: \nun baseline de conteo de caracteres con regresión logística, \nTF-IDF con KNN siguiendo el baseline reportado en el repositorio original, \ny TF-IDF con n-gramas de caracteres combinado con un clasificador más potente.\n\nEl repositorio original reporta los siguientes resultados de referencia:\n\nRandom baseline: ~0.1% de accuracy prediciendo un autor aleatorio entre los 1,000 posibles.\nCharacters Count + Logistic Regression: 29.252% en el conjunto de desarrollo.\nTF-IDF + KNN (25 vecinos, 10K features): 62.128% en desarrollo, aunque requiere varias horas para predecir el conjunto completo.","metadata":{}},{"id":"cc72ddbd-fa7c-4751-aaa1-945ef176de6a","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Configuración del entorno\n\nSe clona el repositorio AI-SOCO que contiene el dataset y se verifica la disponibilidad de GPU. \nPyTorch se usa únicamente para detectar el dispositivo disponible; los modelos del notebook son de scikit-learn.","metadata":{}},{"id":"771b00c7-6e1b-440b-8781-4ac4d75de216","cell_type":"code","source":"import os\nimport glob\nimport string\nimport time\nimport warnings\nimport joblib\nwarnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\n\nimport numpy as np\nimport pandas as pd\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\n\nimport tensorflow as tf\nfrom tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential, load_model\nfrom tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization\nfrom tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam\nfrom tensorflow.keras.callbacks import (\n    ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau\n)\nfrom tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical\n\nfrom sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\nfrom sklearn.metrics import (\n    accuracy_score, f1_score, precision_score,\n    recall_score, confusion_matrix\n)\n\nprint('TensorFlow:', tf.__version__)\nprint('GPU:', tf.config.list_physical_devices('GPU'))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.875619Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.876403Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.882610Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.876375Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.881802Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"TensorFlow: 2.19.0\nGPU: [PhysicalDevice(name='/physical_device:GPU:0', device_type='GPU'), PhysicalDevice(name='/physical_device:GPU:1', device_type='GPU')]\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":18},{"id":"0009a381-cb4c-4c0b-9f3d-dcd7a39254b0","cell_type":"code","source":"MODEL_PATH = '/kaggle/working/models/'\nos.makedirs(MODEL_PATH, exist_ok=True)\nprint(f'Model path: {MODEL_PATH}')\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.884245Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.884665Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.899222Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.884642Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.898283Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Model path: /kaggle/working/models/\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":19},{"id":"1068075e-fe0e-4b1c-8769-8f19ba969ced","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Carga del dataset\n\nEl repositorio contiene los archivos CSV con los metadatos (uid, pid) y las carpetas con los archivos de código fuente. \nSe clona una sola vez y se verifica que el directorio exista antes de volver a clonar.","metadata":{}},{"id":"8206e43e-ef7a-4cb2-a958-ee017697c751","cell_type":"code","source":"REPO_DIR = 'AI-SOCO-REPO'\nDATA_DIR = os.path.join(REPO_DIR, 'data_dir')\n\nif not os.path.exists(REPO_DIR):\n    os.system(f'git clone https://github.com/AliOsm/AI-SOCO.git {REPO_DIR}')\n\nprint('Archivos en data_dir:', os.listdir(DATA_DIR))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.900185Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.900601Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.915449Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.900533Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.914695Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Archivos en data_dir: ['test', 'train.csv', 'train', 'unlabeled_test.csv', 'dev', 'dev.csv']\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":20},{"id":"cf9c95ed-3a45-41d8-9502-944001b8f899","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Carga de los metadatos y los códigos fuente\n\nLos archivos CSV contienen los identificadores de autor (uid) y problema (pid). \nLos códigos fuente están en carpetas separadas nombradas por pid. \nSe cargan ambos y se unen por pid para tener el código fuente junto con la etiqueta de autor.","metadata":{}},{"id":"610f5cdb-d251-4698-848f-baa44ffa6900","cell_type":"code","source":"train_df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(DATA_DIR, 'train.csv'))\ndev_df   = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(DATA_DIR, 'dev.csv'))\ntest_df  = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(DATA_DIR, 'unlabeled_test.csv'))\n\nprint(f'Train: {len(train_df):,}  Dev: {len(dev_df):,}  Test: {len(test_df):,}')\nprint('Autores únicos en train:', train_df['uid'].nunique())\ntrain_df.head()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.916410Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.916752Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.969425Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.916716Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.968621Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Train: 50,000  Dev: 25,000  Test: 25,000\nAutores únicos en train: 1000\n","output_type":"stream"},{"execution_count":21,"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":"   uid    pid\n0  415  27909\n1  415  55938\n2  415  90936\n3  415  56858\n4  415   9447","text/html":"<div>\n<style scoped>\n    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n        vertical-align: middle;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n        vertical-align: top;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe thead th {\n        text-align: right;\n    }\n</style>\n<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"text-align: right;\">\n      <th></th>\n      <th>uid</th>\n      <th>pid</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <th>0</th>\n      <td>415</td>\n      <td>27909</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>1</th>\n      <td>415</td>\n      <td>55938</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>2</th>\n      <td>415</td>\n      <td>90936</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>3</th>\n      <td>415</td>\n      <td>56858</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>4</th>\n      <td>415</td>\n      <td>9447</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n</div>"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":21},{"id":"c7b209b0-4e51-4836-91b1-e9873d97bb31","cell_type":"code","source":"def load_source_codes(df, base_path):\n    source_codes = {}\n    all_files = glob.glob(os.path.join(base_path, '**', '*'), recursive=True)\n    files_only = [f for f in all_files if os.path.isfile(f)]\n\n    for filepath in files_only:\n        name_without_ext = os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(filepath))[0]\n        try:\n            pid = int(name_without_ext)\n            with open(filepath, 'r', encoding='utf-8', errors='ignore') as f:\n                source_codes[pid] = f.read()\n        except (ValueError, OSError):\n            continue\n\n    codes_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(source_codes, orient='index', columns=['source_code'])\n    codes_df.index.name = 'pid'\n\n    cols_to_drop = [c for c in df.columns if c in ['source_code', 'source_code_x', 'source_code_y']]\n    df_clean = df.drop(columns=cols_to_drop)\n    df_merged = pd.merge(df_clean, codes_df, on='pid', how='left')\n\n    loaded = df_merged['source_code'].notna().sum()\n    print(f'{base_path.split(\"/\")[-1]}: {loaded:,} / {len(df_merged):,} códigos cargados')\n    return df_merged\n\n\ntrain_df = load_source_codes(train_df, os.path.join(os.path.abspath(REPO_DIR), 'data_dir', 'train'))\ndev_df   = load_source_codes(dev_df,   os.path.join(os.path.abspath(REPO_DIR), 'data_dir', 'dev'))\ntest_df  = load_source_codes(test_df,  os.path.join(os.path.abspath(REPO_DIR), 'data_dir', 'test'))\n\ntrain_df = train_df.dropna(subset=['source_code'])\ndev_df   = dev_df.dropna(subset=['source_code'])\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.971287Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.971739Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:14.653257Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:10.971716Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:14.652607Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"train: 50,000 / 50,000 códigos cargados\ndev: 25,000 / 25,000 códigos cargados\ntest: 25,000 / 25,000 códigos cargados\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":22},{"id":"5e14f795-9611-4348-880c-9133f76c2574","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Análisis exploratorio\n\nSe analizan seis dimensiones del dataset: distribución de ejemplos por autor, \nlongitud total del código en caracteres, número de líneas, longitud promedio de línea, \nlos autores más representados y la relación entre líneas y caracteres totales. \nLa longitud promedio de línea y el número de líneas son features implícitos del estilo de programación: \nalgunos autores tienden a escribir líneas cortas y separar la lógica, \notros escriben expresiones densas en pocas líneas. \nEstos patrones son los que los modelos intentarán capturar.","metadata":{}},{"id":"30e6010d-da38-4352-92e0-ba05b0158fbc","cell_type":"code","source":"samples_per_author = train_df['uid'].value_counts()\ntrain_df['code_length'] = train_df['source_code'].str.len()\ntrain_df['line_count']  = train_df['source_code'].str.count('\\n')\ntrain_df['avg_line_len'] = train_df['code_length'] / (train_df['line_count'] + 1)\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(16, 9))\n\n# 1. Ejemplos por autor\naxes[0,0].hist(samples_per_author.values, bins=30, color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\naxes[0,0].set_title('Ejemplos por autor')\naxes[0,0].set_xlabel('Número de ejemplos')\naxes[0,0].set_ylabel('Autores')\n\n# 2. Longitud de código\naxes[0,1].hist(train_df['code_length'].clip(upper=5000), bins=50,\n               color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\naxes[0,1].set_title('Longitud del código (chars, truncada a 5000)')\naxes[0,1].set_xlabel('Caracteres')\n\n# 3. Número de líneas\naxes[0,2].hist(train_df['line_count'].clip(upper=200), bins=50,\n               color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\naxes[0,2].set_title('Número de líneas (truncado a 200)')\naxes[0,2].set_xlabel('Líneas')\n\n# 4. Longitud promedio de línea\naxes[1,0].hist(train_df['avg_line_len'].clip(upper=100), bins=50,\n               color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\naxes[1,0].set_title('Longitud promedio de línea')\naxes[1,0].set_xlabel('Chars / línea')\n\n# 5. Top 20 autores con más ejemplos\ntop20 = samples_per_author.head(20)\naxes[1,1].barh(top20.index.astype(str), top20.values, color='steelblue')\naxes[1,1].set_title('Top 20 autores con más ejemplos')\naxes[1,1].set_xlabel('Ejemplos')\naxes[1,1].invert_yaxis()\n\n# 6. Longitud de código vs número de líneas (muestra)\nsample = train_df.sample(2000, random_state=42)\naxes[1,2].scatter(sample['line_count'].clip(upper=200),\n                  sample['code_length'].clip(upper=5000),\n                  alpha=0.3, s=5, color='steelblue')\naxes[1,2].set_title('Líneas vs longitud total (muestra 2k)')\naxes[1,2].set_xlabel('Líneas')\naxes[1,2].set_ylabel('Caracteres')\n\nplt.suptitle('Análisis exploratorio — AI-SOCO', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nprint(f'Ejemplos por autor — media: {samples_per_author.mean():.1f}  '\n      f'min: {samples_per_author.min()}  max: {samples_per_author.max()}')\nprint(f'Longitud — media: {train_df[\"code_length\"].mean():.0f}  '\n      f'mediana: {train_df[\"code_length\"].median():.0f} chars')\nprint(f'Líneas   — media: {train_df[\"line_count\"].mean():.1f}  '\n      f'mediana: {train_df[\"line_count\"].median():.0f}')\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:14.654103Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:14.654421Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.926093Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:14.654397Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.925471Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1600x900 with 6 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"Ejemplos por autor — media: 50.0  min: 50  max: 50\nLongitud — media: 1646  mediana: 1166 chars\nLíneas   — media: 73.8  mediana: 58\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":23},{"id":"26996da4-a15c-4478-834e-bc5e99d214bc","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Guardado, carga de modelos y evaluación\n\nLos modelos de Keras usan los mismos callbacks que en el repositorio SongTextClassifier: \nModelCheckpoint guarda el mejor modelo según val_loss, EarlyStopping detiene el entrenamiento \nsi no hay mejora y ReduceLROnPlateau reduce el learning rate cuando el modelo se estanca. \nSi el archivo del modelo ya existe en disco se carga directamente sin reentrenar, \npermitiendo retomar el trabajo entre sesiones.\n\nLos vectorizadores TF-IDF se guardan con joblib porque no son modelos de Keras. \nSe ajustan solo sobre el conjunto de entrenamiento para evitar filtrar información del dev al modelo.","metadata":{}},{"id":"f01cc8d2-9952-497b-8c8b-d0f89a91db43","cell_type":"code","source":"results = {}\n\ndef get_callbacks(model_name):\n    return [\n        ModelCheckpoint(\n            filepath=MODEL_PATH + f'{model_name}.keras',\n            monitor='val_loss',\n            save_best_only=True,\n            mode='min',\n            verbose=1\n        ),\n        EarlyStopping(\n            monitor='val_loss',\n            patience=5,\n            restore_best_weights=True,\n            verbose=1\n        ),\n        ReduceLROnPlateau(\n            monitor='val_loss',\n            factor=0.5,\n            patience=3,\n            min_lr=1e-7,\n            verbose=1\n        )\n    ]\n\n\ndef load_keras_if_exists(model_name):\n    path = MODEL_PATH + f'{model_name}.keras'\n    if os.path.exists(path):\n        print(f'Modelo cargado desde disco: {model_name}')\n        return load_model(path)\n    return None\n\n\ndef save_vectorizer(name, vec):\n    joblib.dump(vec, MODEL_PATH + f'{name}_vectorizer.joblib')\n    print(f'Vectorizador guardado: {name}_vectorizer.joblib')\n\n\ndef load_vectorizer_if_exists(name):\n    path = MODEL_PATH + f'{name}_vectorizer.joblib'\n    if os.path.exists(path):\n        print(f'Vectorizador cargado: {name}_vectorizer.joblib')\n        return joblib.load(path)\n    return None\n\n\ndef evaluate(name, y_true, y_pred, training_time=None):\n    acc       = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)\n    f1_macro  = f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro',    zero_division=0)\n    f1_weight = f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted', zero_division=0)\n    prec      = precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro', zero_division=0)\n    rec       = recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro',    zero_division=0)\n    results[name] = {\n        'Accuracy':    round(acc,       4),\n        'F1 Macro':    round(f1_macro,  4),\n        'F1 Weighted': round(f1_weight, 4),\n        'Precision':   round(prec,      4),\n        'Recall':      round(rec,       4),\n        'Time(s)':     round(training_time, 2) if training_time else None\n    }\n    print(f'\\n{\"=\"*55}\\n  {name}\\n{\"=\"*55}')\n    print(f'  Accuracy:    {acc:.4f}  ({acc*100:.2f}%)')\n    print(f'  F1 Macro:    {f1_macro:.4f}')\n    print(f'  F1 Weighted: {f1_weight:.4f}')\n    print(f'  Precision:   {prec:.4f}')\n    print(f'  Recall:      {rec:.4f}')\n    if training_time:\n        print(f'  Tiempo:      {training_time:.2f}s')\n    return acc\n\n\ndef plot_full_cm(name, y_true, y_pred):\n    labels = sorted(set(y_true))\n    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=labels)\n    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))\n    plt.imshow(cm, aspect='auto', cmap='Blues', interpolation='nearest')\n    plt.colorbar(label='Predicciones')\n    plt.title(f'Matriz de confusión completa ({len(labels)} autores) — {name}')\n    plt.xlabel('Predicción (uid)')\n    plt.ylabel('Real (uid)')\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.show()\n    diag     = np.diag(cm)\n    row_sums = cm.sum(axis=1)\n    pca      = np.where(row_sums > 0, diag / row_sums, 0)\n    print(f'  Autores con acc = 1.0:  {(pca == 1.0).sum()}')\n    print(f'  Autores con acc = 0.0:  {(pca == 0.0).sum()}')\n    print(f'  Accuracy media por clase: {pca.mean():.4f}')\n\n\ndef plot_per_class_acc_hist(name, y_true, y_pred):\n    labels   = sorted(set(y_true))\n    cm       = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=labels)\n    diag     = np.diag(cm)\n    row_sums = cm.sum(axis=1)\n    pca      = np.where(row_sums > 0, diag / row_sums, 0)\n    plt.figure(figsize=(9, 4))\n    plt.hist(pca, bins=20, color='steelblue', edgecolor='white')\n    plt.axvline(pca.mean(), color='#e74c3c', linestyle='--',\n                label=f'Media: {pca.mean():.3f}')\n    plt.title(f'Distribución de accuracy por autor — {name}')\n    plt.xlabel('Accuracy individual del autor')\n    plt.ylabel('Número de autores')\n    plt.legend()\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.show()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.927058Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.927355Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.945479Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.927333Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.944754Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":24},{"id":"8cfcbf3b-884c-4058-ba88-c421a6ac5614","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Modelo base — Characters Count + MLP\n\nEl baseline del repositorio usa conteo de caracteres con regresión logística. \nAquí se reemplaza el clasificador por una red neuronal densa que corre en GPU. \nLa vectorización es idéntica: un vector de 100 dimensiones con la frecuencia de cada carácter ASCII imprimible. \nLa red aprende combinaciones no lineales de esas frecuencias, \nlo que permite capturar patrones de estilo más sutiles que la combinación lineal de la regresión logística. \nEl repositorio reporta 29.252% de accuracy con Characters+LR, \nlo que sirve como piso de referencia para este modelo.","metadata":{}},{"id":"df78fe6d-0b52-413e-9302-0293c0d074e6","cell_type":"code","source":"PRINTABLE = list(string.printable)\n\ndef char_count_vectorize(texts):\n    matrix = np.zeros((len(texts), len(PRINTABLE)), dtype=np.float32)\n    for i, text in enumerate(texts):\n        for j, ch in enumerate(PRINTABLE):\n            matrix[i, j] = text.count(ch)\n    return matrix\n\n\nle = LabelEncoder()\nle.fit(train_df['uid'])\ny_train    = le.transform(train_df['uid'])\ny_dev      = le.transform(dev_df['uid'])\nnum_classes = len(le.classes_)\n\nX_train_chars = char_count_vectorize(train_df['source_code'].tolist())\nX_dev_chars   = char_count_vectorize(dev_df['source_code'].tolist())\n\nmodel_chars = load_keras_if_exists('chars_mlp')\n\nif model_chars is None:\n    model_chars = Sequential([\n        Dense(256, activation='relu', input_shape=(len(PRINTABLE),)),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.4),\n        Dense(128, activation='relu'),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.3),\n        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')\n    ], name='chars_mlp')\n    model_chars.compile(\n        optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),\n        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n        metrics=['accuracy']\n    )\n    model_chars.summary()\n    t0 = time.time()\n    model_chars.fit(\n        X_train_chars, y_train,\n        validation_data=(X_dev_chars, y_dev),\n        epochs=30,\n        batch_size=256,\n        callbacks=get_callbacks('chars_mlp'),\n        verbose=1\n    )\n    t1 = time.time()\nelse:\n    t0 = t1 = time.time()\n\ny_pred_chars = le.inverse_transform(\n    np.argmax(model_chars.predict(X_dev_chars, verbose=0), axis=1)\n)\ny_dev_labels = le.inverse_transform(y_dev)\n\nevaluate('Characters + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_chars,\n         t1 - t0 if t1 > t0 else None)\nplot_full_cm('Characters + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_chars)\nplot_per_class_acc_hist('Characters + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_chars)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.946465Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.946845Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:26.443496Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:15.946823Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:26.442650Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Modelo cargado desde disco: chars_mlp\n\n=======================================================\n  Characters + MLP\n=======================================================\n  Accuracy:    0.6187  (61.87%)\n  F1 Macro:    0.6154\n  F1 Weighted: 0.6154\n  Precision:   0.6628\n  Recall:      0.6187\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1000x800 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"  Autores con acc = 1.0:  67\n  Autores con acc = 0.0:  9\n  Accuracy media por clase: 0.6187\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 900x400 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":25},{"id":"a3611ee6-6504-490d-8581-4998f520efd0","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## TF-IDF como herramienta de métodos cuantitativos\n\nTF-IDF (Term Frequency - Inverse Document Frequency) es una medida cuantitativa que asigna un peso numérico a cada término de un documento dentro de un corpus. En el contexto de M4, puede interpretarse como una función de similitud vectorial que permite comparar documentos — en este caso, fragmentos de código fuente — de forma matemáticamente rigurosa.\n\nLa fórmula se compone de dos factores:\n\n**TF (frecuencia del término):** mide cuántas veces aparece un término `t` en el documento `d` relativo al total de términos del documento:\n\n```\nTF(t, d) = frecuencia de t en d / número total de términos en d\n```\n\n**IDF (frecuencia inversa de documento):** penaliza los términos que aparecen en muchos documentos del corpus, ya que son menos discriminativos:\n\n```\nIDF(t, D) = log( N / df(t) )\n\ndonde:\n  N    = número total de documentos en el corpus\n  df(t) = número de documentos que contienen el término t\n```\n\nEl peso final de cada término es el producto de ambos factores:\n\n```\nTF-IDF(t, d, D) = TF(t, d) × IDF(t, D)\n```\n\nCada documento queda representado como un vector en un espacio de dimensión igual al vocabulario. La similitud entre dos documentos se calcula entonces con la similitud coseno entre sus vectores:\n\n```\nsimilitud(A, B) = (A · B) / (||A|| × ||B||)\n```\n\nEste valor está acotado entre 0 (ninguna similitud) y 1 (documentos idénticos en distribución de términos). Es exactamente la métrica que KNN usa internamente para encontrar los 25 vecinos más cercanos, y lo que convierte a TF-IDF+KNN en un método cuantitativo de similitud: la probabilidad de que un código pertenezca a un autor se estima a partir de la distribución de los vecinos más similares en el espacio vectorial.\n\nLa variante con `sublinear_tf=True` usada en el Modelo 3 aplica una transformación logarítmica a la frecuencia del término (`1 + log(TF)`) para reducir el efecto de términos muy frecuentes dentro de un mismo documento, lo que mejora la discriminación entre autores en textos largos.","metadata":{}},{"id":"052c8202-1de7-4600-80bc-2435240b87ce","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Modelo 2 — TF-IDF + MLP\n\nEl segundo baseline del repositorio usa TF-IDF con KNN. \nKNN no corre en GPU porque necesita comparar cada ejemplo contra todo el conjunto de entrenamiento en CPU. \nSe reemplaza por una red neuronal densa que opera sobre los mismos vectores TF-IDF. \nLa entrada es dispersa, por lo que se convierte a denso antes de pasar a las capas. \nLa mayor capacidad de la red respecto al modelo base permite capturar interacciones \nmás complejas entre los términos del código. \nEl repositorio reporta 62.128% de accuracy con TF-IDF+KNN como punto de referencia.","metadata":{}},{"id":"b4482579-c164-4147-af34-fc26ff608011","cell_type":"code","source":"tfidf_w = load_vectorizer_if_exists('tfidf_word')\n\nif tfidf_w is None:\n    tfidf_w = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=10000)\n    X_train_tfidf = tfidf_w.fit_transform(train_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n    save_vectorizer('tfidf_word', tfidf_w)\nelse:\n    X_train_tfidf = tfidf_w.transform(train_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n\nX_dev_tfidf = tfidf_w.transform(dev_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n\n# Convertir a denso en batches para no saturar RAM\nBATCH = 5000\n\ndef sparse_to_dense_batched(X):\n    parts = []\n    for start in range(0, X.shape[0], BATCH):\n        parts.append(X[start:start+BATCH].toarray().astype(np.float32))\n    return np.vstack(parts)\n\n\nX_train_tfidf_d = sparse_to_dense_batched(X_train_tfidf)\nX_dev_tfidf_d   = sparse_to_dense_batched(X_dev_tfidf)\nprint(f'Train: {X_train_tfidf_d.shape}  Dev: {X_dev_tfidf_d.shape}')\n\nmodel_tfidf = load_keras_if_exists('tfidf_mlp')\n\nif model_tfidf is None:\n    model_tfidf = Sequential([\n        Dense(512, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_tfidf_d.shape[1],)),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.4),\n        Dense(256, activation='relu'),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.3),\n        Dense(128, activation='relu'),\n        Dropout(0.2),\n        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')\n    ], name='tfidf_mlp')\n    model_tfidf.compile(\n        optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),\n        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n        metrics=['accuracy']\n    )\n    model_tfidf.summary()\n    t0 = time.time()\n    model_tfidf.fit(\n        X_train_tfidf_d, y_train,\n        validation_data=(X_dev_tfidf_d, y_dev),\n        epochs=30,\n        batch_size=256,\n        callbacks=get_callbacks('tfidf_mlp'),\n        verbose=1\n    )\n    t1 = time.time()\nelse:\n    t0 = t1 = time.time()\n\ny_pred_tfidf = le.inverse_transform(\n    np.argmax(model_tfidf.predict(X_dev_tfidf_d, verbose=0), axis=1)\n)\n\nevaluate('TF-IDF + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_tfidf,\n         t1 - t0 if t1 > t0 else None)\nplot_full_cm('TF-IDF + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_tfidf)\nplot_per_class_acc_hist('TF-IDF + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_tfidf)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:26.444686Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:26.445054Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:00:49.156744Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:26.445030Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:00:49.156039Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Vectorizador cargado: tfidf_word_vectorizer.joblib\nTrain: (50000, 10000)  Dev: (25000, 10000)\nModelo cargado desde disco: tfidf_mlp\n\n=======================================================\n  TF-IDF + MLP\n=======================================================\n  Accuracy:    0.6986  (69.86%)\n  F1 Macro:    0.7075\n  F1 Weighted: 0.7075\n  Precision:   0.7370\n  Recall:      0.6986\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1000x800 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"  Autores con acc = 1.0:  91\n  Autores con acc = 0.0:  2\n  Accuracy media por clase: 0.6986\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 900x400 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":26},{"id":"df2c670d-8dc7-4461-8f9d-3cea0002c4f7","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Modelo 3 — TF-IDF n-gramas de caracteres + MLP profunda\n\nEste modelo combina la vectorización con n-gramas de caracteres, \nque captura patrones de formato y estilo más finos que los tokens de palabras, \ncon la arquitectura de red más profunda del conjunto. \nSe reduce max_features a 20,000 (en lugar de 50,000) para que la matriz densa \nquepa en la RAM disponible en Kaggle. Con 50,000 features la conversión a denso \nconsume más de 13 GB solo para los datos de entrenamiento, lo que causa el kernel restart. \n20,000 features mantiene la ventaja de los n-gramas de caracteres sin saturar la memoria.","metadata":{}},{"id":"7c9195f7-0993-4c99-a8fd-4b7f319afca8","cell_type":"code","source":"tfidf_c = load_vectorizer_if_exists('tfidf_char')\n\nif tfidf_c is None:\n    tfidf_c = TfidfVectorizer(\n        analyzer='char',\n        ngram_range=(2, 4),\n        max_features=20000,   # reducido de 50k para evitar OOM\n        sublinear_tf=True\n    )\n    X_train_char = tfidf_c.fit_transform(train_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n    save_vectorizer('tfidf_char', tfidf_c)\nelse:\n    X_train_char = tfidf_c.transform(train_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n\nX_dev_char = tfidf_c.transform(dev_df['source_code'].astype(str))\n\nX_train_char_d = sparse_to_dense_batched(X_train_char)\nX_dev_char_d   = sparse_to_dense_batched(X_dev_char)\nprint(f'Train: {X_train_char_d.shape}  Dev: {X_dev_char_d.shape}')\n\nmodel_char = load_keras_if_exists('char_mlp')\n\nif model_char is None:\n    model_char = Sequential([\n        Dense(512, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_char_d.shape[1],)),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.5),\n        Dense(256, activation='relu'),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.4),\n        Dense(128, activation='relu'),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.3),\n        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')\n    ], name='char_mlp')\n    model_char.compile(\n        optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=5e-4),\n        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n        metrics=['accuracy']\n    )\n    model_char.summary()\n    t0 = time.time()\n    model_char.fit(\n        X_train_char_d, y_train,\n        validation_data=(X_dev_char_d, y_dev),\n        epochs=30,\n        batch_size=256,\n        callbacks=get_callbacks('char_mlp'),\n        verbose=1\n    )\n    t1 = time.time()\nelse:\n    t0 = t1 = time.time()\n\ny_pred_char = le.inverse_transform(\n    np.argmax(model_char.predict(X_dev_char_d, verbose=0), axis=1)\n)\n\nevaluate('TF-IDF char n-gramas + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_char,\n         t1 - t0 if t1 > t0 else None)\nplot_full_cm('TF-IDF char n-gramas + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_char)\nplot_per_class_acc_hist('TF-IDF char n-gramas + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_char)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:00:49.157814Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:00:49.158145Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.459773Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:00:49.158118Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.459028Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Vectorizador cargado: tfidf_char_vectorizer.joblib\nTrain: (50000, 20000)  Dev: (25000, 20000)\nModelo cargado desde disco: char_mlp\n\n=======================================================\n  TF-IDF char n-gramas + MLP\n=======================================================\n  Accuracy:    0.9109  (91.09%)\n  F1 Macro:    0.9109\n  F1 Weighted: 0.9109\n  Precision:   0.9175\n  Recall:      0.9109\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1000x800 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"  Autores con acc = 1.0:  321\n  Autores con acc = 0.0:  0\n  Accuracy media por clase: 0.9109\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 900x400 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":27},{"id":"7ce584e1-f372-40ee-bf69-ff6517aec160","cell_type":"code","source":"print('Modelos guardados:')\nfor f in sorted(os.listdir(MODEL_PATH)):\n    size = os.path.getsize(os.path.join(MODEL_PATH, f)) / (1024*1024)\n    print(f'  {f}  ({size:.1f} MB)')\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.461933Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.462169Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.467835Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.462150Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.467009Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Modelos guardados:\n  ast_mlp.keras  (1.9 MB)\n  char_mlp.keras  (120.6 MB)\n  chars_mlp.keras  (2.2 MB)\n  tfidf_char_vectorizer.joblib  (0.6 MB)\n  tfidf_mlp.keras  (62.0 MB)\n  tfidf_word_vectorizer.joblib  (0.3 MB)\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":28},{"id":"79514588-c11a-4582-935f-c4694c12c6e5","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Árboles sintácticos abstractos (AST) para atribución de autoría\n\nUn Árbol Sintáctico Abstracto es la representación estructural del código fuente que genera un compilador durante el análisis sintáctico. A diferencia del texto plano, el AST captura la jerarquía lógica del programa: qué nodos son hijos de cuáles, cómo se anidan los bloques, qué operaciones se aplican sobre qué operandos.\n\nLa ventaja para atribución de autoría es que el AST es invariante a cambios superficiales: dos programas con distinta indentación, distinto nombre de variables o distintos comentarios pueden tener estructuras de árbol muy similares si fueron escritos con el mismo estilo lógico. Esto permite capturar el 'fingerprint' de un programador a un nivel más profundo que los n-gramas de caracteres.\n\nEl módulo `ast` de Python permite extraer este árbol directamente. Para código C++ como el del dataset AI-SOCO se puede usar `tree-sitter`, que soporta múltiples lenguajes. En este notebook se usa Python como ejemplo de la técnica, ya que `ast` está disponible sin instalación adicional.","metadata":{}},{"id":"a61defe4-86a6-4d08-87fe-4b166aae26f8","cell_type":"code","source":"import ast as ast_module\nimport collections\n\ndef extract_ast_features(source_code, lang='python'):\n    \"\"\"\n    Extrae un vector de features del AST de un fragmento de código.\n    Cada feature es el conteo de nodos de cada tipo en el árbol.\n\n    El tipo de nodo refleja decisiones estructurales del programador:\n    - FunctionDef: cuántas funciones define\n    - For / While: preferencia por iteración\n    - If / IfExp: densidad de condicionales\n    - Call: frecuencia de llamadas a funciones\n    - ListComp / DictComp: uso de comprensiones\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        tree = ast_module.parse(source_code)\n    except SyntaxError:\n        return {}\n\n    node_counts = collections.Counter()\n    for node in ast_module.walk(tree):\n        node_counts[type(node).__name__] += 1\n\n    return dict(node_counts)\n\n\ndef ast_vectorize(texts, vocab=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Convierte una lista de códigos fuente a una matriz de features AST.\n    vocab: lista de tipos de nodo a usar como columnas.\n           Si es None, se infiere del corpus completo.\n    \"\"\"\n    features_list = [extract_ast_features(t) for t in texts]\n\n    if vocab is None:\n        all_keys = set()\n        for f in features_list:\n            all_keys.update(f.keys())\n        vocab = sorted(all_keys)\n\n    matrix = np.zeros((len(texts), len(vocab)), dtype=np.float32)\n    for i, feat in enumerate(features_list):\n        for j, key in enumerate(vocab):\n            matrix[i, j] = feat.get(key, 0)\n\n    return matrix, vocab\n\n\n# Ejemplo sobre una muestra del dataset para validar la extracción\nsample_codes = train_df['source_code'].head(500).tolist()\nX_ast_sample, ast_vocab = ast_vectorize(sample_codes)\n\nprint(f'Features AST extraídos: {len(ast_vocab)} tipos de nodo')\nprint(f'Shape matriz sample: {X_ast_sample.shape}')\nprint(f'Tipos de nodo más frecuentes:')\ntotals = X_ast_sample.sum(axis=0)\ntop_idx = totals.argsort()[::-1][:15]\nfor idx in top_idx:\n    print(f'  {ast_vocab[idx]:20s}: {int(totals[idx]):,}')\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.468943Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.469411Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.513940Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.469386Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.513011Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Features AST extraídos: 0 tipos de nodo\nShape matriz sample: (500, 0)\nTipos de nodo más frecuentes:\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":29},{"id":"b3bef009-131a-4c6b-a40a-5bec42e291c1","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Visualización del AST\n\nSe visualiza el árbol de un fragmento de código simple para entender qué captura cada nodo. La profundidad del árbol y la distribución de tipos de nodo son features cuantitativos que caracterizan el estilo de programación.","metadata":{}},{"id":"29bf8a4b-46d8-4c79-93ea-2847cdd8925a","cell_type":"code","source":"def print_ast(source_code, max_depth=3):\n    \"\"\"Imprime el AST de un fragmento de código hasta una profundidad máxima.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        tree = ast_module.parse(source_code)\n    except SyntaxError as e:\n        print(f'SyntaxError: {e}')\n        return\n\n    def _walk(node, depth=0):\n        if depth > max_depth:\n            return\n        indent = '  ' * depth\n        fields = [f for f, _ in ast_module.iter_fields(node)]\n        print(f'{indent}{type(node).__name__}  {fields}')\n        for child in ast_module.iter_child_nodes(node):\n            _walk(child, depth + 1)\n\n    _walk(tree)\n\n\nexample_python = '''\ndef solve(n):\n    result = 0\n    for i in range(n):\n        if i % 2 == 0:\n            result += i\n    return result\n'''\nprint('AST del fragmento de ejemplo:')\nprint('-' * 40)\nprint_ast(example_python)\n\n# Distribución de tipos de nodo en el dataset completo\nX_ast_train, ast_vocab = ast_vectorize(train_df['source_code'].tolist())\nprint(f'\\nShape final: {X_ast_train.shape}')\nprint(f'Tipos de nodo: {len(ast_vocab)}')\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.514926Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.515238Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:03:41.387802Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:03:39.515211Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-29T16:03:41.387033Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"AST del fragmento de ejemplo:\n----------------------------------------\nModule  ['body', 'type_ignores']\n  FunctionDef  ['name', 'args', 'body', 'decorator_list', 'returns', 'type_comment', 'type_params']\n    arguments  ['posonlyargs', 'args', 'vararg', 'kwonlyargs', 'kw_defaults', 'kwarg', 'defaults']\n      arg  ['arg', 'annotation', 'type_comment']\n    Assign  ['targets', 'value', 'type_comment']\n      Name  ['id', 'ctx']\n      Constant  ['value', 'kind']\n    For  ['target', 'iter', 'body', 'orelse', 'type_comment']\n      Name  ['id', 'ctx']\n      Call  ['func', 'args', 'keywords']\n      If  ['test', 'body', 'orelse']\n    Return  ['value']\n      Name  ['id', 'ctx']\n\nShape final: (50000, 0)\nTipos de nodo: 0\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":30},{"id":"d1e0e57c-aab5-4ee5-99be-d8e3c72db126","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Modelo sobre features AST\n\nSe entrena una MLP sobre los vectores de conteo de nodos AST. Si este modelo obtiene accuracy razonable, confirma que la estructura sintáctica del código contiene información discriminativa del autor, independientemente del vocabulario o los n-gramas. La comparación con los modelos TF-IDF permite cuantificar qué aporta la estructura lógica respecto al análisis textual.","metadata":{}},{"id":"1e22af13-9eae-428d-8046-b870f5ef9efa","cell_type":"code","source":"X_ast_dev, _ = ast_vectorize(dev_df['source_code'].tolist(), vocab=ast_vocab)\n\nmodel_ast = load_keras_if_exists('ast_mlp')\n\nif model_ast is None:\n    model_ast = Sequential([\n        Dense(256, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_ast_train.shape[1],)),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.4),\n        Dense(128, activation='relu'),\n        BatchNormalization(),\n        Dropout(0.3),\n        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')\n    ], name='ast_mlp')\n    model_ast.compile(\n        optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),\n        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n        metrics=['accuracy']\n    )\n    model_ast.summary()\n    t0 = time.time()\n    model_ast.fit(\n        X_ast_train, y_train,\n        validation_data=(X_ast_dev, y_dev),\n        epochs=30,\n        batch_size=256,\n        callbacks=get_callbacks('ast_mlp'),\n        verbose=1\n    )\n    t1 = time.time()\nelse:\n    t0 = t1 = time.time()\n\ny_pred_ast = le.inverse_transform(\n    np.argmax(model_ast.predict(X_ast_dev, verbose=0), axis=1)\n)\n\nevaluate('AST features + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_ast,\n         t1 - t0 if t1 > t0 else None)\nplot_full_cm('AST features + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_ast)\nplot_per_class_acc_hist('AST features + MLP', y_dev_labels, y_pred_ast)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-29T16:03:41.388844Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-29T16:03:41.389464Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-29T16:03:45.107349Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-29T16:03:41.389439Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-